  // Original, self-contained blind-test materials. They are shown only on each
  // 30-day checkpoint, so the learner can complete a genuine first attempt.
  const STAGE_TEST_MATERIALS = [
    {
      listeningTitle: "A Busy Saturday",
      listeningScript: `Emma usually gets up at seven, but today she gets up at eight. It is Saturday, and she does not have to work. She makes eggs and coffee for breakfast. At ten, she walks to the grocery store near her home. She buys milk, fruit, and rice. In the afternoon, she meets her friend Leo at a small café. Emma orders tea because she has already had coffee. They talk about a movie and make plans for Sunday. In the evening, Emma feels tired, so she stays home and reads.`,
      readingTitle: "Daniel's New Routine",
      readingText: `Daniel moved to a new city one month ago. At first, everything felt difficult. He did not know the streets, and he did not have friends nearby. His new job starts at nine, so every morning he gets up at seven. He takes the subway and usually arrives twenty minutes early. After work, he used to go straight home. Now his routine is different. On Mondays, he goes to a small gym near his office. On Wednesdays, he studies English at the library. On Friday evening, he has dinner with two people from work. Daniel still misses his hometown, but the new city is beginning to feel comfortable. He knows where to shop, how to get around, and who to call when he wants to talk. He says that one small plan each day helped him build a new life.`
    },
    {
      listeningTitle: "A Hotel Mix-up",
      listeningScript: `Clerk: Good evening. How can I help you?\nGuest: Hi, I have a reservation under the name Lin, but I can't find the confirmation email.\nClerk: That's all right. May I see your passport?\nGuest: Of course. I booked a room for three nights.\nClerk: I found the reservation, but it begins tomorrow.\nGuest: Oh no. I must have entered the wrong date. Do you have any rooms available tonight?\nClerk: We have one smaller room on the second floor. You could stay there tonight and move to your original room tomorrow.\nGuest: That would be fine. Is the price the same?\nClerk: The smaller room costs twenty dollars less. I'll update the booking now.`,
      readingTitle: "The Train to Westport",
      readingText: `Nina was traveling alone for the first time. She had planned the trip carefully: an early flight, a train from the airport, and a short walk to her hotel. The flight arrived on time, and she found the station without trouble. Then she made one small mistake. She got on the train at platform six without checking its final destination.\n\nAfter twenty minutes, Nina noticed that the names on the station signs were not on her map. She asked another passenger, “Does this train go to Westport?” The passenger shook his head and explained that Nina was traveling north instead of west. She needed to get off at the next stop, cross to the opposite platform, and take a train back to Central Station.\n\nNina felt worried because her phone battery was almost empty. She wrote the directions on paper and sent a quick message to the hotel. At the next stop, an employee showed her which ticket to buy and where to wait. The return train was late, but Nina finally reached Westport at eight in the evening.\n\nThe hotel clerk had saved her room. Nina was tired and hungry, but she was also proud. She had asked clear questions, checked each new step, and solved the problem without giving up. Before her next trip, she decided, she would always read the destination on the train before getting on.`
    },
    {
      listeningTitle: "A Choice about Work",
      listeningScript: `Last year, Marcus received two job offers. The first company offered a higher salary and a famous name, but the office was almost two hours from his home. The second company was smaller and paid less. However, its office was nearby, and employees could work from home twice a week. At first, Marcus focused only on the money. Then he wrote down what a normal week would look like in each job. He realized that the longer commute would take nearly fifteen hours every week. That was time he wanted to spend with his young daughter and on his health. Marcus chose the smaller company. Six months later, he says the decision was right for his family, although he sometimes wonders what he could have learned at the larger firm.`,
      readingTitle: "The Empty Lot on Pine Street",
      readingText: `For years, the empty lot on Pine Street was a place people hurried past. Weeds covered the ground, old bottles collected near the fence, and no one seemed to know who was responsible for it. Then a local teacher named Rosa asked a simple question at a neighborhood meeting: “Could this become something useful?”\n\nRosa suggested turning the lot into a community garden. The idea sounded attractive, but the problems appeared immediately. The land belonged to the city, the soil needed to be tested, and the project had no money. Some residents also worried that a garden would create noise or attract insects. Instead of promising quick results, Rosa formed a small group to investigate each concern.\n\nThe group contacted the city and learned that residents could use the land for three years if they maintained it. A local college tested the soil for free. Because part of the ground was not safe for growing food directly, volunteers built raised garden beds and filled them with clean soil. A hardware store donated tools, while families contributed small amounts for seeds.\n\nThe first season did not go perfectly. Rabbits ate several plants, and people argued about watering duties. The group responded by creating a clear schedule and building a simple fence. By late summer, the garden produced tomatoes, beans, herbs, and more zucchini than anyone expected. Children from Rosa's school visited on Fridays to measure plants and learn where food came from. Older residents often sat in the shaded area and talked.\n\nThe garden did not solve every problem in the neighborhood. It required time, organization, and repeated conversations. Its most important result, however, may not have been the vegetables. People who had lived near one another for years finally learned each other's names. The empty lot became a place where residents could contribute something small and see a shared result.`
    },
    {
      listeningTitle: "Should We Cancel the Meeting?",
      listeningScript: `Maya: Are we still having the product meeting at two?\nJon: I was about to ask you the same thing. Priya's train has been delayed, and she probably won't get here before three.\nMaya: We could start without her, but she's the one who spoke with the customer.\nJon: Right, and if we make a decision now, we may have to go over everything again later.\nMaya: What if we use the time to review the test results? We don't need Priya for that part.\nJon: That could work. Then we could discuss the customer's feedback when she arrives.\nMaya: I'll send everyone a quick message so they know the plan has changed.\nJon: Good idea. Could you also ask Priya to call us if the delay gets worse?\nMaya: Sure. By the way, have you seen the latest numbers? They're better than I expected.\nJon: Not yet. Let's pull them up before everyone gets here.`,
      readingTitle: "Why Familiar English Can Still Sound Unfamiliar",
      readingText: `Many learners have had the same confusing experience: they know every word in a sentence when they see it, but they cannot recognize the sentence when a fluent speaker says it. The problem is not always vocabulary. Often, it is the difference between the careful pronunciation learners expect and the way sounds change in connected speech.\n\nIn natural conversation, speakers do not give every word equal weight. Important nouns, verbs, adjectives, and numbers usually receive stress. Small grammar words may become shorter and quieter. In the sentence “Can you send it to me?”, the words “send” and “me” may be much clearer than “can,” “you,” or “to.” A learner waiting to hear six separate dictionary forms may miss the whole message.\n\nSounds also connect across word boundaries. The final consonant of one word can move smoothly into the vowel at the beginning of the next. “Pick it up” may sound like one continuous unit rather than three separate words. Speakers may also use common contractions and reduced forms. These changes are not careless mistakes; they help language flow efficiently.\n\nThe solution is not simply to play long videos again and again. Short, focused comparison is more useful. A learner can first listen without text and write down any stressed words or meaning they notice. Next, they can check an accurate English transcript and identify the exact place where the expected sound differed from the real one. Replaying that small section and copying its rhythm helps connect sound with meaning. Finally, the learner should listen again without the transcript.\n\nIt is important to keep the goal realistic. Understanding does not require hearing every sound. Fluent listeners also use the situation, the speaker's goal, and their knowledge of the topic to predict meaning. Training becomes more effective when learners combine these clues with closer attention to sound. Over time, phrases that once seemed to disappear begin to feel like familiar units.`
    },
    {
      listeningTitle: "A Four-day Schedule",
      listeningScript: `Host: Several departments at North Valley College tested a four-day schedule for three months. Employees worked the same total number of hours, but most offices closed on Friday. Supporters said the extra day reduced commuting and gave staff more uninterrupted personal time. Managers also reported fewer short absences and said that teams began questioning meetings that had no clear purpose. However, the change created problems for students who needed help at the end of the week. Some employees also found the longer workdays tiring, especially when they had family responsibilities in the evening. One department responded by keeping a small Friday team and allowing those employees to take Monday off instead. Another returned to five days but shortened its afternoon meetings. The college has not decided whether to make the schedule permanent. It will compare response times, employee surveys, unfinished work, and operating costs. Leaders say the goal is not to declare one schedule perfect. They want to understand which arrangement produces reliable service without exhausting the people who provide it.`,
      readingTitle: "The Four-day Week: A Better System or a Better Story?",
      readingText: `The idea of a four-day workweek attracts attention for an obvious reason: many people would like more time away from work. Yet the most serious proposals are not simply offering an extra day off. They are asking whether organizations can produce the same results in less time by changing how work is organized.\n\nSupporters argue that a shorter week can improve both well-being and performance. Employees may return to work with more energy, take fewer sick days, and have more time for family responsibilities. Companies may also find it easier to attract and keep skilled workers. In some trials, teams maintained their output after reducing meetings, protecting periods of focused work, and removing tasks that existed only because “we have always done it this way.”\n\nHowever, the results are not automatic. A business that simply pushes five days of work into four longer, more stressful days may create exhaustion rather than freedom. Customer-facing organizations must decide how to provide service when employees are away. Hospitals, restaurants, transportation systems, and small stores cannot all close for the same extra day. Even in office jobs, workers may have different preferences. A parent might value a weekday at home, while another employee may prefer five shorter days.\n\nMeasuring success also requires care. Productivity is easy to claim but difficult to define. A sales team can count completed deals, while a design or research team may not see the results of today's work for months. Short trials may receive an extra burst of effort because employees want the experiment to succeed. That energy may not continue once the arrangement becomes normal. Organizations also need to examine whether unfinished work is quietly being completed at home.\n\nThe strongest versions of a four-day policy focus on redesign rather than speed. Teams identify their essential results, reduce low-value meetings, make decisions with fewer approval steps, and create clearer periods when colleagues should not expect immediate replies. Leaders must also protect the shortened schedule. If every “urgent” request takes back the fifth day, employees receive the pressure of the old system without its predictability.\n\nA four-day week, then, is neither a universal solution nor an unrealistic dream. Its value depends on the type of work, the needs of customers, the design of the schedule, and the honesty of the measurement. The larger lesson may be that working habits should not continue only because they are familiar. Even organizations that keep a five-day week can learn from the question: which activities truly produce value, and which merely fill the available time?`
    },
    {
      listeningTitle: "The Place between Home and Work",
      listeningScript: `Host: Today we're talking about “third places”—the cafés, parks, libraries, and community spaces that are neither home nor work. Dr. Ellis, why do these places matter?\nDr. Ellis: They create low-pressure contact. You may not become close friends with everyone at a local café, but seeing familiar faces can still produce a sense of belonging. Repeated small contact also helps useful local information move between people.\nHost: Some people would say online communities now serve the same purpose.\nDr. Ellis: They can serve part of it, especially for people who are isolated by distance, disability, or a lack of local options. But physical places also connect us to people we did not choose through an algorithm. That kind of unplanned contact has value.\nHost: Not every public place feels welcoming to everyone.\nDr. Ellis: That's true. A park may be nearby but difficult to use if its paths are unsafe. A café may be friendly but too expensive for someone to visit regularly. Access includes price, opening hours, transportation, disability access, and whether people feel they have permission to stay.\nHost: Cities are expensive. How can they protect such spaces?\nDr. Ellis: They can begin by treating libraries, safe sidewalks, benches, and public rooms as social infrastructure rather than decoration. Buildings can also serve several purposes: a school cafeteria, for example, might host an evening language group. Private businesses matter too, but a community should not require everyone to buy something in order to belong.\nHost: The benefits must be hard to measure.\nDr. Ellis: They are. You can count visits, but trust and belonging may appear only indirectly—in health, local knowledge, or people's willingness to help during an emergency.\nHost: So the issue isn't choosing online or offline life.\nDr. Ellis: Exactly. It is creating enough different ways for people to participate.`,
      readingTitle: "The Quiet Value of Places Where Nothing Special Happens",
      readingText: `When people describe the places that shape a city, they often mention homes, offices, schools, and famous public buildings. Less attention is given to ordinary spaces where people spend time without a major purpose: a library reading room, a bench near a playground, a neighborhood café, a barber shop, or a public square. Social researchers sometimes call these “third places” because they exist between the private world of home and the formal world of work.\n\nA third place does not need to be beautiful or important. Its value often comes from being nearby, affordable, and easy to enter. People can stay for a reasonable amount of time without needing an invitation. Regular visitors begin to recognize one another, even if their conversations remain brief. A person who works from home may exchange only a few words with the same café employee each morning, but that small contact can still provide rhythm and recognition.\n\nThese weak connections are easy to underestimate because they are not close friendships. Yet they can influence how supported a person feels. A familiar neighbor may share information about a local service, notice when an older resident has not appeared for several days, or simply make a difficult week feel less anonymous. Third places also allow people of different ages and backgrounds to see one another as more than abstract groups. They do not remove disagreement, but they can make other members of a community feel real.\n\nNot everyone experiences these spaces in the same way. A café that feels welcoming to one customer may be too expensive or noisy for another. A park may be physically close but difficult to use if its paths are unsafe or if people feel unwelcome there. Some spaces appear public while quietly discouraging anyone who cannot pay. For a third place to serve a broad community, access matters as much as location. This includes opening hours, transportation, disability access, safety, and the expectation that different kinds of people have a right to remain.\n\nDigital communities complicate the picture. Online spaces can connect people who would never meet locally, including those with rare interests, health conditions, or identities that are not supported nearby. For someone who cannot easily leave home, an online group may provide essential friendship rather than a weaker copy of “real” life. At the same time, digital platforms usually organize attention through personal choices and recommendation systems. Users see people they follow or content selected to hold their interest. Physical third places create more accidental contact with people who are not already part of one's chosen network.\n\nEconomic pressure has reduced many traditional gathering places. Independent shops struggle with rent, public libraries face budget cuts, and new development may favor spaces designed for quick consumption. Even seating can become controversial. Some property owners remove benches to discourage behavior they consider undesirable, but the result also affects older adults, parents, people with disabilities, and anyone who needs to rest. Decisions about simple objects reveal a larger question: who is a public space actually for?\n\nCommunities do not have to recreate an idealized past. New forms of third places can emerge in shared workshops, community gardens, sports groups, cultural centers, or buildings that serve several purposes at different times of day. A school cafeteria might host evening language classes. An underused store could become a temporary art and meeting space. Streets can support interaction when they include shade, seating, safe crossings, and reasons to walk. None of these designs guarantees community, but each creates an opportunity for repeated contact.\n\nThe benefits of such places are also difficult to measure. A city can count library visits or park users, but belonging does not fit neatly into a spreadsheet. The effects may appear indirectly through public health, trust, local knowledge, or people's willingness to help during an emergency. Because the results are spread across time and institutions, no single organization may feel responsible for investing in them.\n\nProtecting third places therefore requires a broader definition of infrastructure. Roads and internet connections allow people and information to move. Libraries, parks, and welcoming public rooms allow relationships and trust to develop. Both systems support daily life, even when their value becomes most visible only after they fail. The quiet strength of a third place is that nothing extraordinary needs to happen there. People return, recognize one another, and gradually feel that they are not passing through the world alone.`
    }
  ];

